Ask HN: Why wasn't USB designed to handle peer-to-peer data transfer?
text: A friend and I were wondering why USB wasn't designed to accommodate the peer-to-peer (computer-to-computer) data transfer use case? In the DOS and Win 3.1 days we used to transfer files across computers via either serial or parallel port connections. It seems that USB "crossover cables" do exist but they either have some kind of active electronics in the middle, or expressly say "do not use this to connect two computers together".

Show HN: Weekly AI newsletter to reconnect to Earth
text:
Research proves that >= 120 min/week of time in nature dramatically improves mental well being.

This is a free newsletter that will send you an email once a week with nearby suggestions for nature adventures (hikes and POIs).

This is an attempt at fixing the problem: "I want to spend more time in nature but it takes too much planning." It's easy now to make going out in nature a part of your hygiene, with curated options easy to choose from.

This is built on top of a backend I'm currently building that is processing millions of hikes and POIs with machine learning to extrapolate the many insights that constitute the decision process our code goes through to send you your weekly newsletter.

Hope you like it!
